eturned to VMI as the acting director of Cadet Affairs in 1997 and served in this post until he was promoted to his current position in 2000  He received the VMI Achievement Medal in 2002  Following his graduation from VMI  Green served as an assistant instructor for the Department of Civil Engineering  From 1969 to 1970  he served as a lieutenant with the First Combat Engineer Battalion  First Infantry Division in the Republic of Vietnam  After receiving his master s degree in engineering from the University of Virginia in 1972  Green joined Wiley   Wilson in Lynchburg  Va  as a project engineer manager and then as vice president  In 1987  he was promoted to president of Wiley   Wilson  That year Green returned to VMI for one year as a visiting professor of Civil Engineering and holder of the Wachtmeister Chair in Science and Engineering  From 1998 until 2003  Green held the Fred C  Culpepper  40 adjunct professor in Civil and Environmental Engineering and is a Professional Engineer  VMI Foundation Keydet Club Alumni Webcams Directories My VMI  RESOURCES   Title IX  Health   Safety   IT   Site Index Parents   Families   Cadets   Non discrimination Statement   Privacy   THE VMI PHILOSOPHY The VMI experience is framed by relevant education within a military environment  It s an education that develops character  fosters a lifelong appreciation of physical fitness engenders a sense of responsibility to others  and cultivates the ability to master adversity  VIRGINIA MILITARY INSTITUTE Lexington  Virginia 24450 General Information   540  464 7230  Admissions  admissions vmi edu 